		<div id="comment_body_64969109"><p>Certainly, but also I'm sure the deaths attributable to loss of jobs are non-zero. (probably due to depression, heart attack, and alcohol issues)  (ask perplexity.ai about it... it'll quote studies )<br>e.g. short term:</p><p><div class="quote"><p> Job loss is associated with a 73% increase in the probability of death, equivalent to adding 10 years to a person's age</p><span class="substr"> </span></div><p> <a href="https://drexel.edu/news/archive/2014/july/unemployment-study" title="drexel.edu">https://drexel.edu/news/archiv...</a> [drexel.edu] </p><p>e.g. long term:</p><p><div class="quote"><p>Even 20 years after displacement, there is a 10%-15% increase in annual death hazards for displaced workers4.</p></div><p> (from ~2006 looking back to people laid off in the 70s and 80s  <a href="http://www.econ.ucla.edu/tvwachter/papers/sullivan_vonwachter_qje.pdf" title="ucla.edu">http://www.econ.ucla.edu/tvwac...</a> [ucla.edu]  )</p><p>Thus it's probably more true than not that CEOs of large companies have caused deaths by layoff, though the 1 death per $1M seems pretty high to me</p></div>
	</div>

