<div id="comment_64968911" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64968911" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64968911" name="comment_link_64968911" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23530223&amp;cid=64968911" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64968911)" >Manager class need to manage</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64968911" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64968911); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~bb_matt">bb_matt</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~bb_matt">( 5705262 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64968911"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64968911"><p>When I was a young'un my Ma and Pa told me "Those that can, do. Those that can't, teach."</p><p>It was a rubbish saying - total wank really - but that's how some people think.<br>There's perhaps a tiny kernel of truth in it, just as there's a kernel of truth in:</p><p>"Those that can, do. Those that can't get into management."</p><p>There's a huge amount of sentiment around how terrible management can be and generally is, but the bottom line is it's all about middle management.<br>Middle managers are usually people just trying to forge<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
